            "The modeline is the area at the bottom of nearly every buffer that shows information about that buffer--including the file path for file buffers, the current major mode, and the current Evil state.")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "You can interact with the modeline. If you hover over the modeline with the mouse, it will tell you what clicking on that area will do.")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "The modeline, and the toolbar, are both invaluable sources of information for beginners."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "window" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "Window")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "An Emacs"
            (code
              "window")
            "is closer to the modern concept of a"
            (code
              "pane")
            ". A window can only display one buffer at a time."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "frame" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "Frame")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "An Emacs"
            (code
              "frame")
            "is the equivalent of the modern concept of a"
            (code
              "window")
            ". It's the box that displays the Emacs application. A frame can hold multiple Emacs windows and minibuffers simultaneously."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "minibuffer" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "Minibuffer")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "A minibuffer is a"
            (code
              "buffer")
            "that is intended to be temporary. Usually they display some information while you are in the middle of a command or other action, and close automatically when you finish or abort the action/command."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "mode" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "Mode")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "Buffers have both"
            (code
              "major")
            "and"
            (code
              "minor")
            "modes. If you open a"
            (code
              ".lisp")
            "file, the file will automatically open in"
            (code
              "lisp-mode")
            "."
            (code
              "lisp-mode")
            "is a"
            (code
              "major-mode")
            ". ~auto-save-mode=,"
            (code
              "evil-mode")
            ","
            (code
              "company-mode")
            ","
            (code
              "hl-mode")
            ", etc. are"
            (code
              "minor")
            "modes. Only one"
            (code
              "major")
            "mode can be active in one buffer. Multiple"
            (code
              "minor")
            "modes can be active in a buffer.")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "Modes provide syntax highlighting, specialized commands, and various features intended to improve the editing experience."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "state" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "State")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "This is more specific to the"
            (code
              "evil-mode")
            "package. States describe the keyboard cursor. In normal state"))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "workspaces-projects" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "Workspaces & Projects")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "Doom includes packages that provide workspace and project functionality, allowing you to more effectively separate groups of buffers and give you the ability to quickly search multiple projects. The functionality idiomatic of workspaces and projects aren't native to Emacs, but they are conveniently provided by Doom Emacs through several packages."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "packages" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "Packages")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "Emacs packages are equivalent of \"extensions\" or \"plugins\". Not to be confused with"
            (i
              "Common Lisp packages")
            "which are an entirely separate idiom and functionality.")))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "keybinding-basics" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Keybinding Basics")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Doom Emacs have vanilla Emacs keybindings and vim-style keybindings (see:"
          (code
            "evil")
          "in the"
          (code
            "init.el")
          "file) enabled by default.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          (code
            "C")
          "is the control key."
          (code
            "M")
          "is the meta/option/alt key."
          (code
            "s")
          "is the super/command/windows key."
          (code
            "SPC")
          "is the space key"
          (code
            "ESC")
          "is the escape key.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          (code
            "C-x")
          "means \"Hold control then press x\"."
          (code
            "C-c C-c")
          "means \"Hold control then press c, then hold control then press c\"."
          (code
            "SPC f f")
          "means \"Press the space key then f then f\".")))
    (article :class "almighty-section"
      (h2 :id "survival-emacs" :class "almighty-section-title"
        "SURVIVAL EMACS")
      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
        "When you first begin with this book, I assume you at least don't know Emacs keybindings. If you know Vim/Neovim style bindings, then you'll know how to do basic text navigation and editing, search and replace, etc. I'll teach you the basics of how to get around and get started following along with the next Lisp chapter. Importantly, you won't need to learn any keybindings at all; you can mostly pretend Emacs is a plain text editor. Thus, in this chapter I'll teach you how to:")
      (ul :class "org-ul"
        (li
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "Create & Open a file buffer using the menu."))
        (li
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "Read the modeline."))
        (li
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "Insert text."))
        (li
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "Save a file buffer using the menu."))
        (li
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "View a list of open buffers in the menu.")))
      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
        "Additionally, there are some behaviors in Emacs that may be confusing while doing basic text editing. I'll tell you about these behaviors ahead of time so it's less frustrating when you first begin.")
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "creating-opening-file-buffers" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Creating & Opening File Buffers")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "In Emacs, creating a new file buffer and opening an existing file into a buffer are nearly the same action, making it somewhat confusing.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Let's say you want to create a new file. In the menu, navigate to"
          (code
            "File->Visit New File")
          ". A new minibuffer will open. In the top left of the minibuffer it will say \"Find File\" and show the path to the current directory. To make a new file there, type in the name of the file you want to create, like \"abc.txt\" or \"main.lisp\", then press"
          (code
            "Enter")
          ". A new, empty buffer with that name will open."
          (i
            "The file doesn't exist until you save it."))
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "To navigate to other directories from that minibuffer, you can type the name of a subdirectory, or you can press"
          (code
            "Backspace")
          "to navigate to a parent directory instead.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Now let's say you want to open an existing file. In the menu, navigate to"
          (code
            "File->Open File")
          ". The identical minibuffer will open. Navigate to your file, type in its name, and press"
          (code
            "Enter")
          "to open the file."))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "reading-the-modeline" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Reading The Modeline")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "With a file buffer open, take a look at the bar at the bottom of the buffer. It contains important information. It's contents, from left to right:")
        (ul :class "org-ul"
          (li
            (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
              "An icon showing the current"
              (code
                "evil-mode")
              "state."))
          (li
            (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
              "An integer showing the buffer size."))
          (li
            (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
              "The path to the current file/buffer."))
          (li
            (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
              "Two numbers separated by a colon. These show the current line and column of the cursor. Example:"
              (code
                "50:20")
              "means"
              (code
                "line 50, column 20")))))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "inserting-text" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Inserting Text")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "By default, you are in"
          (code
            "evil-mode")
          "'s"
          (code
            "Normal State")
          ". We want to initially avoid learning any complicated systems of text editing. To do that, we can switch to"
          (code
            "Emacs State")
          ". Type"
          (code
            "C-z")
          ". In the modeline in the bottom left, you should see the icon change, probably to"
          (code
            "E")
          ", indicating that you are in"
          (code
            "Emacs State")
          ". In this state:")
        (ul :class "org-ul"
          (li
            (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
              "You have access to all of Emacs' keybindings."))
          (li
            (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
              "You can insert, highlight, cut, copy, paste, and delete text as you usually would.")))
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "You will need to switch to"
          (code
            "Emacs State")
          "every time you open a new buffer.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "To switch out of"
          (code
            "Emacs State")
          "and back into"
          (code
            "Normal State")
          ", type"
          (code
            "C-z")
          "again."))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "saving-files" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Saving Files")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "You can save a file using your standard keybinding"
          (code
            "s-s")
          ", or you can save with the menu. Navigate to"
          (code
            "File->Save")
          "."))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "view-a-list-of-open-buffers" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "View A List Of Open Buffers")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "You can view a list of open buffers and switch to one in the menu. Navigate to"
          (code
            "Buffers")
          ". Buffers that have names like"
          (code
            "*Messages*")
          "are special Emacs buffers. All others should be file buffers.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "If you click on one of the buffers, the window with the keyboard cursor active will switch to that buffer."))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "kill-close-a-buffer" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Kill/Close A Buffer")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "To close a buffer, navigate to"
          (code
            "File->Close")
          "."))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "strange-behavior" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Strange Behavior")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "That'll get you started with the basics. There are few strange behaviors to look out for, though.")
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "i-typed-something-once-but-it-got-repeated-several-times" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "\"I typed something once but it got repeated several times.\"")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "In"
            (code
              "Emacs State")
            ", if you type"
            (code
              "C-u")
            "and then a number"
            (code
              "n")
            ", the next thing you type will be repeated"
            (code
              "n")
            "times. If you type"
            (code
              "C-u 8 d")
            "you will type 8 d's.")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "This is useful behavior when you know what's happening, confusing and frustrating when you don't. It's usually more of a problem in Evil"
            (code
              "Normal State")
            "because you don't even have to type"
            (code
              "C-u")
            ", and if you type"
            (code
              "8")
            ", go into"
            (code
              "Insert State")
            "and type in a bunch of code and then type"
            (code
              "ESC")
            "to go back to"
            (code
              "Normal State")
            ", all of the code will be repeated 8 times."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "i-can-t-type-anything-the-window-seems-locked" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "\"I can't type anything; the window seems locked.\"")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "Look at the beginning of the buffer name. Does it have a Lock icon? You may have accidentally typed"
            (code
              "C-x C-q")
            "or"
            (code
              "SPC t r")
            ", putting the buffer into read-only mode. Type"
            (code
              "C-x C-q")
            "or"
            (code
              "SPC t r")
            "again to make the buffer editable again."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "i-typed-something-and-the-buffer-changed" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "\"I typed something and the buffer changed.\"")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "You may have accidentally closed or switched the buffer. You can try switching back using the method above, or you can type"
            (code
              "C-w C-u")
            "to undo whatever the heck you did. We'll see later that the"
            (code
              "C-w C-u")
            "("
            (code
              "winner-undo")
            ") command has some other uses.")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "And if you accidentally undid something that you want to"
            (i
              "redo")
            ", you can type"
            (code
              "C-w C-r")
            "."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "i-typed-something-and-some-minibuffer-or-prompt-came-up-and-i-want-to-just-get-rid-of-it" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "\"I typed something and some minibuffer or prompt came up and I want to just get rid of it.\"")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "Typically this happens to me when I accidently type"
            (code
              "C-x k")
            "to kill/close a buffer. Whatever you did, you can cancel whatever action you are in the middle of by typing"
            (code
              "C-g")
            "a few times."
            (code
              "C-g")
            "is a universal command for canceling some action."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "my-buffer-has-a-file-open-but-i-can-only-see-part-of-it-or-perhaps-none-of-it-at-all" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "\"My buffer has a file open but I can only see part of it (or perhaps none of it at all).\"")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "If you're sure you have a file buffer open to a file that exists and has data in it, then you may be a victim of"
            (i
              "narrowing")
            ". You can confirm by looking at the modeline: At the beginning of the buffer/file path in the modeline, if you see two arrows, one above the other, pointing to each other, then the buffer has been narrowed.")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "To unnarrow or"
            (i
              "widen")
            ", switch to"
            (code
              "Normal State")
            "and type"
            (code
              "SPC b -")
            "("
            (code
              "doom/toggle-narrow-buffer")
            ")."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "i-cut-some-text-but-when-i-try-to-paste-some-other-text-appears" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "\"I cut some text, but when I try to paste, some other text appears.\"")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "Did you cut some text, delete a word with"
            (code
              "C-backspace")
            "? Is that word the one being pasted?")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "You are experiencing expected behavior of the kill ring. You can undo everything the normal way you undo any text operation using"
            (code
              "s-z")
            ".")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "To avoid this behavior, you need to use"
            (code
              "backspace")
            "or"
            (code
              "delete")
            "alone (erasing a character at a time). I'll cover killing later.")))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "speeding-up-w-keybindings" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Speeding Up w/Keybindings")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "If during the next chapter you find yourself limited by using the menu for doing things, notice that in the menu there are keybindings printed next to nearly every command available in there. Try using some of the keybindings for your most frequently used commands (like"
          (code
            "Eval Defun")
          "or"
          (code
            "Compile Defun")
          ")."))))
  (article :class "almighty-chapter"
    (h1 :id "lisp-setup-use" :class "almighty-chapter-title"
      "LISP SETUP & USE")
    (article :class "almighty-section"
      (h2 :id "installing-lisp" :class "almighty-section-title"
        "INSTALLING LISP")
      "nil")
    (article :class "almighty-section"
      (h2 :id "survival-lisp-commands" :class "almighty-section-title"
        "SURVIVAL LISP COMMANDS")
      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
        "Beyond simple file/buffer operations and text editing are Common Lisp-specific concepts and commands. This chapter will quickly run through the essentials for getting started.")
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "compiling-evaluating-lisp-code-from-the-buffer" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Compiling/Evaluating Lisp Code From the Buffer")
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "form" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "Form")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "To"
            (i
              "compile")
            "a form, place the cursor anywhere in a form then in the menu navigate to"
            (code
              "Sly->Compilation->Compile Defun")
            ". This works for other forms, not just"
            (code
              "defun")
            "(which we'll learn about later).")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "To"
            (i
              "evaluate")
            "the form place the cursor anywhere in the form then navigate to"
            (code
              "Sly->Evaluation->Eval Defun")
            "."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "variable" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "Variable")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "If a global variable is set, you can get the value of the variable anywhere it is in a Lisp file.")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "Set the cursor at the end of the variable then navigate to"
            (code
              "Sly->Evaluation->Eval last expression")
            ". This works for individual symbols and other forms, too."))
        (article :class "almighty-section"
          (h4 :id "file" :class "almighty-section-title"
            "File")
          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
            "To compile a whole file, navigate to"
            (code
              "Sly->Compilation->Compile and Load File")
            ".")))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "lisp-images" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Lisp Images")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "An important concept that has deep implications for Lisp development is the Lisp Image.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "When you first open a Common Lisp file in Emacs, a new REPL session and Lisp image is created. Code is then loaded, compiled, and executed in the image. It is sometimes likened to an operating system.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Some operations that you perform will modify image-level settings. We will see some examples later.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "An image can be saved and restored. We'll learn how to do that at the appropriate time."))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "using-the-repl" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Using the REPL")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Since a REPL was opened when you opened a Common Lisp file, you"
          (i
            "can")
          "switch to it using the standard menu navigation for switching buffers. However, the entire window will be taken up with the REPL, which may not be what you want.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "If you would like a REPL opened in a"
          (i
            "minibuffer")
          "under your Lisp buffer, then do the following: With a Lisp file open and the cursor in the buffer, type"
          (code
            "SPC m '")
          ". A Lisp REPL will be opened. The REPL/image is \"attached\" to the Emacs instance. If you open a different Lisp file and compile the code, it will be loaded into the same image."))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "structural-editing" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Structural Editing")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Editing Lisp code can be tricky at first.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "If you delete a closing-parenthesis, all of the code between and including the opening and closing parentheses will be deleted.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Deleting an end-quote will do the same.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "This is call \"structural editing\". It prevents unbalanced parentheses or quotes. However, there are some circumstances where it actually makes it difficult to fix unbalanced parentheses (usually because of copy/pasting code).")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "There can be a lot of confusing behavior with structural editing. To turn it off, type"
          (code
            "M-x lispy-mode")
          "to toggle"
          (code
            "lispy-mode")
          "off. With lispy-mode off, you will have more freedom, but less help from the editor. As the spirit moves, you can toggle it on and play around with it. We'll cover some useful features of structural editing later."))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "the-lisp-debugger" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "The Lisp Debugger")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "We will take a closer look at the debugger and errors in the chapter on errors and conditions, but before you get to that section you'll probably cause the debugger to open and display a message like this:")
        (pre :class "example" :id "orga42efff"
          ":AWS fell through ECASE expression.
Wanted one of (:DEVELOPMENT :PRODUCTION).
   [Condition of type SB-KERNEL:CASE-FAILURE]

Restarts:
 0: [RETRY] Retry SLY evaluation request.
 1: [*ABORT] Return to SLY's top level.
 2: [ABORT] abort thread (#<THREAD tid=11923 \"slynk-worker\" RUNNING {70071BE463}>)")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "In this situation, you can do two things:")
        (ol :class "org-ol"
          (li
            (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
              "Navigate the cursor to one of the"
              (code
                "restarts")
              "and press"
              (code
                "Enter")
              "."))
          (li
            (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
              "Type the key corresponding to the"
              (code
                "restart")
              "(0 for [RETRY], 1 for [*ABORT], etc.) to select it.")))
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "In the beginning, it's safest to choose whichever restart says"
          (code
            "[*ABORT]")
          ". If your list of restarts is too long, it will be truncated and you might need to highlight and type"
          (code
            "Enter")
          "on a"
          (code
            "Show More")
          "option.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "However, if you want to, you can give Common Lisp's debugger a test drive. If you cause an error, try leaving the debugger open, fixing the bug in your code (make sure to compile it), and then selecting a"
          (code
            "RETRY")
          "restart if one is available. This is one of Common Lisp's most powerful"
          (b
            "built-in")
          "features."))))
  (article :class "almighty-chapter"
    (h1 :id "lisp-fundamentals" :class "almighty-chapter-title"
      "LISP FUNDAMENTALS")
    (article :class "almighty-section"
      (h2 :id "syntax-grammar" :class "almighty-section-title"
        "SYNTAX & GRAMMAR")
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "s-expressions" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "S-expressions")
        (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
          (pre
            (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
              "(+ 3 4)")))
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "This is a Common Lisp"
          (code
            "s-expression")
          ". S-expressions are made of indivisible units called"
          (code
            "atoms")
          "--such as the"
          (code
            "symbol")
          (code
            "+")
          "and the number"
          (code
            "3")
          "--and divisible units called"
          (code
            "lists")
          ". They are also called"
          (code
            "forms")
          ".")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Atoms evaluate to themselves.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "The first atom in a list is evaluated as a function name. The rest of the arguments are evaluated before being passed to the function.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Symbols, other than the first one in a list, are evaluated as variables.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Some forms have special evaluation rules and are called special forms."))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "prefix-notation" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "Prefix Notation")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Math operations in Common Lisp are probably different than what you're used to.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Common Lisp math operations use"
          (code
            "prefix notation")
          ": the math operator is a function that comes at the beginning of the parenthesis, and all numbers afterward evaluated using that operator, from left to right. In school, we learn math using"
          (code
            "infix notation")
          ", where the operators are placed between each number.")
        (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
          (pre
            (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
              "(+ (* 5 5 5) (/ 18 2) (- 20 3)) ; using infix notation: 5 * 5 * 5 + 18 / 2 + 20 - 3"))))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "more-complicated-s-expression" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "More complicated s-expression")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Let's look at a slightly more complicated example of Common Lisp syntax:")
        (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
          (pre
            (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
              "(defun cube (x)
  (* x x x))")))
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "After the opening parenthesis comes"
          (code
            "defun")
          ", a built-in"
          (code
            "special form")
          ". Special forms have different evaluation rules compared to regular function calls."
          (code
            "defun")
          "is used to define a function. The function above is given the name"
          (code
            "cube")
          ". After giving the function a name, we define it's"
          (code
            "parameters")
          ", the data it takes as ~arguments= to run the operations inside the function. The function takes one argument:"
          (code
            "x")
          ".")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Notice that"
          (code
            "cube")
          "isn't evaluated as a variable. The"
          (code
            "x")
          "in"
          (code
            "(x)")
          "isn't initially interpreted as a function to be called.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          (code
            "defun")
          "is a special operator where the first argument it receives is a symbol designating the name to give the function, and the second argument is a list of arguments that the function is expected to receive when it's called. The forms that follow afterward are called the"
          (code
            "body")
          "of the function.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "There are several other special forms with their own syntax. We'll cover them later."))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "evaluation-rules" :class "almighty-section-title"
