    (article :class "almighty-section"
      (h2 :id "lists" :class "almighty-section-title"
        "LISTS")
      (article :class "almighty-section"
        (h3 :id "in-the-beginning-was-the-cons" :class "almighty-section-title"
          "In The Beginning Was The Cons")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Lists are the most flexible and fundamental data structure in Common Lisp.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "The easiest way to make a list is like this:")
        (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
          (pre
            (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
              "(list 'this 'is 'a 'list)
;; => (THIS IS A LIST)")))
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "That list contains four symbols. The more common way to create the above list is to use"
          (code
            "quote")
          ":")
        (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
          (pre
            (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
              "(quote (this is a list))
;; => (THIS IS A LIST)")))
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "Or, using a reader macro:")
        (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
          (pre
            (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
              "'(this is a list)
;; => (THIS IS A LIST)")))
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "If you are experienced in other languages like Python or JavaScript, you might think Lisp's lists are the same as in those languages. However, that isn't the case.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "The more fundamental data structure that lists are built on top of are cons cells. Lisp's lists are"
          (b
            "linked lists")
          "of cons cells.")
        (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
          (pre
            (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
              "(cons 'this nil)

(cons 'this (cons 'is nil))

(cons 'this (cons 'is (cons 'a (cons 'linked (cons 'list nil)))))")))
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "A cons cell has two parts or slots: a"
          (code
            "car")
          "and a"
          (code
            "cdr")
          ". The car contains some data, and the cdr contains either more cons cells or"
          (code
            "nil")
          "."
          (code
            "nil")
          "terminates the linked list branch.")
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "More importantly, and maybe confusingly, Common Lisp code is written using these very same cons cells.")
        (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
          (pre
            (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
              ";; Parenthesis, then function name \"cons\", then data, all establishing a nested linked list.
(cons 'defun (cons 'sum (cons (cons 'x (cons 'y nil))
                              (cons
                               (cons '+
                                (cons 'x (cons 'y nil)))
                               nil))))

;; Parenthesis, then function name \"defun\", then data, all establishing a nested linked list.
(defun sum (x y)
  (+ x y))

;; quoting the \"sum\" definition returns the same output as the nested cons cells above.
(quote
 (defun sum (x y)
   (+ x y)))

;;... which is different from returning a string containing that code.
\"(defun sum (x y)
   (+ x y))\"

;; How is it different? Because I can evaluate it as code.
(eval
 (quote
  (defun sum (x y)
    (+ x y))))

;; And I can do the same to the cons cells above
(eval
 (cons 'defun (cons 'sum (cons (cons 'x (cons 'y nil))
                               (cons
                                (cons '+
                                      (cons 'x (cons 'y nil)))
                                nil)))))")))
        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
          "The line between \"code\" and \"data\" that is clearly drawn in other languages like Python or JavaScript"
          (i
            "does not exist")
          "in Lisp, owing to the fact that code and data both share the same syntax and data structure."))
      (article :class "almighty-section"
