                                                              (article :class "almighty-chapter"
                                                                (h1 :id "beyond-lists" :class "almighty-chapter-title"
                                                                  "BEYOND LISTS")
                                                                (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                  (h2 :id "oop" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                    "OOP")
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "what-are-common-lisp-classes" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "What are Common Lisp classes?")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "Classes")
                                                                      "are user-defined data types that group related data. Unlike the OOP systems found elsewhere, Common Lisp classes don't package data and an API for acting on that data together in the same module. Instead, classes define types of data that can be targeted or specialized for by"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "typecase")
                                                                      "forms and generic functions/methods."))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "class-basics" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Class Basics")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defclass creature ()
  ((name :initarg :name
         :initform nil
         :accessor creature-name)
   (territory :initarg :territory
              :initform \"Earth\"
              :accessor creature-territory)))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "This is the basic structure of a class definition."
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "defclass")
                                                                      "takes at least three arguments: a name, a list of classes to inherit from, and"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "slot")
                                                                      "definitions.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Use"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "make-instance")
                                                                      "to make an instance of the class.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(make-instance 'creature :name \"Cat\")")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Slot definitions can take a number of options. The essentials are:")
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "initargs" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "=:initargs=")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Defines the keyword argument used for setting the slot's value when creating an instance of the class.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(defparameter *cat* (make-instance 'creature :name \"Cat\"))"))))
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "initform" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "=:initform=")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Defines the default value of the slot if none is provided at the time of instantiation.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(creature-territory *cat*)
                                        ; => \"Earth\"")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "When a class"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "inherits")
                                                                        "from another class, its definition includes everything in the superclass plus the additional slots it's own definition includes. You can also overwrite the definition of a superclass's slot.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(defclass person (creature)
  ((name :initarg :creature-name
         :initform \"John Doe\"
         :accessor person-name)
   (marrital-status :initarg :marrital-status
                    :initform :single
                    :accessor marrital-status)))

(defparameter *john-doe* (make-instance 'person :marrital-status :married))

(person-name *john-doe*)
                                        ; => \"John Doe\""))))
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "accessor" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "=:accessor=")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Defines the"
                                                                        (i
                                                                          "generic method")
                                                                        "that can be used to both access and modify the slot's value.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(creature-name *cat*)
                                        ; => \"Cat\"

(setf (creature-name *cat*) \"Tiger\")

(creature-name *cat*)
                                        ; => \"Tiger\"")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Because accessors are generic methods specialized on instances of the class that defines them, two classes can define accessors with the same name without any conflicts.")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "In practice, you'll often see accessors that follow a"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "<class-name>-<slot-name>")
                                                                        "convention for clarity."))
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "reader-writer" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "=:reader= & =:writer=")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Usually you want an accessor--a method that allows you to both read and write to a slot. In some cases, as in condition definitions, you may want to only allow the program to read from a slot. In that case, you can replace"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          ":accessor")
                                                                        "with"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          ":reader")
                                                                        ".")))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "custom-constructors" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Custom Constructors")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "While you can manually called"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "make-instance")
                                                                      "all the time, it's common to define a custom constructor for objects.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defun make-creature (name territory)
  (make-instance 'creature :name name :territory territory))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "In addition to reducing typing in the simple case, custom constructors are also where you can filter input, add type-checking with"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "etypecase")
                                                                      ", modify data before making an instance, etc."))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "generic-functions-methods" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Generic Functions & Methods")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Classes describe what an object"
                                                                      (i
                                                                        "has")
                                                                      ", but they don't say anything about what an object"
                                                                      (i
                                                                        "does")
                                                                      ". That's because in Common Lisp,"
                                                                      (i
                                                                        "classes")
                                                                      "don't have"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "methods")
                                                                      ";"
                                                                      (i
                                                                        "generic functions")
                                                                      "have methods.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defclass person ()
  ((name :initarg :name :initform nil :accessor person-name)))
(defgeneric greet (instance))
(defmethod greet ((this person))
  (format t \"~&Hello, ~a~%\" (person-name this)))
(defparameter *john-doe* (make-instance 'person :name \"John Doe\"))
(greet *john-doe*)
                                        ; Hello, John Doe
                                        ;  => NIL")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "defgeneric")
                                                                      "defines a generic function. Generic functions define an interface for, and then dispatch to,"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "generic methods")
                                                                      "."
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "greet")
                                                                      "defines an interface: it only requires an instance of a class. When a call to"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "greet")
                                                                      "is made, it looks at the object instance passed and dispatches to the method specialized on that generic function."))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "extending-oop-systems" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Extending OOP Systems")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Every generic method can be wrapped in code that will modify its behavior before it's called, after it's called, or both (\"around\"). Methods can be specialized on more than one type. A method call is sent to the method that is most \"specific\"--the method that specializes on types that are closest to the ones passed to the method as argument. A more specific method can call the next less specific method in a chain of methods.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Method combination is a technique that involves chaining together some mixture of the above techniques. Extending an OOP system in Common Lisp will involve some degree of method combination."))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "before-after-around-methods" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Before, After, & Around Methods")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Before, after, and around methods are methods that modify the behavior of a method--called the primary method--at certain points in the method call.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defmethod greet :before ((this person))
  (format t \"~&Oh, what a nice looking young man. Let me go talk to him...~%\"))
(greet *john-doe*)
                                        ; Oh, what a nice looking young man. Let me go talk to him...
                                        ; Hello, John Doe
                                        ;  => NIL

(defmethod greet :after ((this person))
  (format t \"~&(Strong handshake, good man.)~%\"))
(greet *john-doe*)
                                        ; Oh, what a nice looking young man. Let me go talk to him...
                                        ; Hello, John Doe
                                        ; (Strong handshake, good man.)
                                        ;  => NIL")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Before and after methods are fairly self explanatory. Primary methods are the core of the onion; before and after methods are two layers around the core.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "After methods are a layer outside of before and after methods.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defmethod greet :around ((this person))
  (format t \"I should get off the couch and go talk to people.\"))
(greet *john-doe*)
; I should get off the couch and go talk to people. => NIL")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "However, they require extra work to use.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defmethod greet :around ((this person))
  (format t \"I should get off the couch and go talk to people.\")
  (call-next-method)
  (format t \"Here's my card, ~a. Let me know if you need help learning Lisp.\" (person-name this)))
(greet *john-doe*)
; I should get off the couch and go talk to people.
; Oh, what a nice looking young man. Let me go talk to him...
; Hello, John Doe
; (Strong handshake, good man.)
; Here's my card, John Doe. Let me know if you need help learning Lisp. => NIL")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "call-next-method")
                                                                      "calls the next most specific version of"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "greet")
                                                                      "for the"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "*john-doe*")
                                                                      "object, which is the before method. The before method automatically calls the next method--the primary method--so we don't have to call"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "call-next-method")
                                                                      "in it. Same goes for the around method.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Since"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "call-next-method")
                                                                      "works by calling the next most specific method, it can be used to chain together methods in other ways.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defclass smart-person (person) ())
(defclass rich-person (person) ())
(defclass dumb-person (person) ())
(defclass poor-person (person) ())

(defparameter *musk* (make-instance 'smart-person :name \"Mr. Musk\"))

(defmethod greet ((this smart-person))
  (format t \"~&(Wow, it's ~a! I can't believe he's here!)~%\" (person-name this)))
(greet *musk*)
                                        ; I should get off the couch and go talk to people.
                                        ; Oh, what a nice looking young man. Let me go talk to him...
                                        ; (Wow, it's Mr. Musk! I can't believe he's here!) <- Primary method response.
                                        ; (Strong handshake, good man.)
                                        ; Here's my card, Mr. Musk. Let me know if you need help learning Lisp. => NIL
(defmethod greet ((this smart-person))
  (format t \"~&(Wow, it's ~a! I can't believe he's here!)~%\" (person-name this))
  (call-next-method))
(greet *musk*)
                                        ; I should get off the couch and go talk to people.
                                        ; Oh, what a nice looking young man. Let me go talk to him...
                                        ; (Wow, it's Mr. Musk! I can't believe he's here!) <- Primary method response.
                                        ; Hello, Mr. Musk                                  <- Next most specific method response.
                                        ; (Strong handshake, good man.)
                                        ; Here's my card, Mr. Musk. Let me know if you need help learning Lisp. => NIL")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "All this indirection can be confusing. If you are extending some OOP system and your method isn't being called for some reason, you can use"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "compute-applicable-methods")
                                                                      "to find out which methods a particular combination of arguments to a certain function name apply to those arguments.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(compute-applicable-methods #'greet (list (make-instance 'person :name \"Micah\")))
                                        ; => (#<STANDARD-METHOD COMMON-LISP-USER::GREET :AROUND (PERSON) {7009D091C3}>
                                        ; #<STANDARD-METHOD COMMON-LISP-USER::GREET :AFTER (PERSON) {7009D091E3}>
                                        ; #<STANDARD-METHOD COMMON-LISP-USER::GREET :BEFORE (PERSON) {7009D09203}>
                                        ; #<STANDARD-METHOD COMMON-LISP-USER::GREET (PERSON) {7009D09223}>)

(compute-applicable-methods #'greet (list (make-instance 'smart-person :name \"Mr. Musk\")))
                                        ; => (#<STANDARD-METHOD COMMON-LISP-USER::GREET (SMART-PERSON) {700792E213}>
                                        ; #<STANDARD-METHOD COMMON-LISP-USER::GREET :AROUND (PERSON) {7009D091C3}>
                                        ; #<STANDARD-METHOD COMMON-LISP-USER::GREET :AFTER (PERSON) {7009D091E3}>
                                        ; #<STANDARD-METHOD COMMON-LISP-USER::GREET :BEFORE (PERSON) {7009D09203}>
                                        ; #<STANDARD-METHOD COMMON-LISP-USER::GREET (PERSON) {7009D09223}>)"))))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "pretty-printing-objects" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Pretty Printing Objects")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "There are several generic functions worth knowing about when you first start using Lisp. One of them is"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "print-object")
                                                                      "--used for pretty printing objects.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defmethod print-object ((this creature) stream)
  (with-slots (name territory) this
    (format stream \"~a ~a\" name territory)))

(make-instance 'creature :name \"Cat\" :territory \"House\")
                                        ; => Cat House")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "with-slots")
                                                                      "is a useful macro for dealing with object data. You could use"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "let")
                                                                      "instead...")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(let ((name (slot-value this 'name))
      (territory (slot-value this 'territory)))
  ...)")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "But"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "with-slots")
                                                                      "is nicer for this purpose. There is also"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "with-accessors")
                                                                      ", which is equivalent to using"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "creature-name")
                                                                      "and"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "creature-territory")
                                                                      "instead of"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "slot-value")
                                                                      ".")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "In the case of"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "print-object")
                                                                      ", it's safest to stick with"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "with-slots")
                                                                      "or"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "slot-value")
                                                                      ". If you change the accessor, you might end up with difficult to debug errors when printing objects.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Another common error would be to try to print slot values that aren't bound. That's why you should probably have"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        ":initform")
                                                                      "set to"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "nil")
                                                                      "if you have no other desired default value; you won't have trouble with"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "UNBOUND SLOT")
                                                                      "errors.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defclass beverage ()
  ((name :initarg :name :accessor name)
   (amount :initarg :amount :accessor amount)))

(make-instance 'beverage)
                                        ; => #<BEVERAGE {700B0D0343}>

(defmethod print-object ((this beverage) stream)
  (with-slots (name amount) this
    (format stream \"~a ~a\" name amount)))

(make-instance 'beverage)
                                        ; => #<BEVERAGE <<error printing object>> {7008470343}>")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Since we didn't bind any of the slots--neither in the call to"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "make-instance")
                                                                      "nor in the class definition with"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        ":initform")
                                                                      "--we get the"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "<<error printing object>>")
                                                                      "message. We have two choices to fix the problem: check for unbound slots in the"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "print-object")
                                                                      "method using"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "slot-boundp")
                                                                      ", or prevent slots from being unbound when the object is initialized.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          ";; Check for unbound slots.
(defmethod print-object ((this beverage) stream)
  (let ((name (when (slot-boundp this 'name) (slot-value this 'name)))
        (amount (when (slot-boundp this 'amount) (slot-value this 'amount))))
    (format stream \"~a ~a\" name amount)))

(make-instance 'beverage)
                                        ; => NIL NIL

;; Prevent slots from being unbound by specifying a default value of nil.
(defclass beverage ()
  ((name :initarg :name :initform nil :accessor name)
   (amount :initarg :amount :initform nil :accessor amount)))

(defmethod print-object ((this beverage) stream)
  (with-slots (name amount) this
    (format stream \"~a ~a\" name amount)))

(make-instance 'beverage)
                                        ; => NIL NIL")))
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "print-unreadable-object" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "=print-unreadable-object=")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "By default, Lisp will provide a printed representation of an object that looks like this:")
                                                                      (pre :class "example" :id "org15a4993"
                                                                        "#<BEVERAGE {700B0D0343}>")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "This representation contains two important piece of information:")
                                                                      (ol :class "org-ol"
                                                                        (li
                                                                          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                            (code
                                                                              "#<BEVERAGE ...>")
                                                                            ": This is a"
                                                                            (code
                                                                              "BEVERAGE")
                                                                            "object."))
                                                                        (li
                                                                          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                            (code
                                                                              "{700B0D0343}")
                                                                            ": This is where the object is in memory.")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Consider this:")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(defclass warm-beverage (beverage) ())
(defclass cold-beverage (beverage) ())
(values (make-instance 'warm-beverage :name \"Coffee\" :amount 1000)
        (make-instance 'cold-beverage :name \"Coffee\" :amount 1000))
                                        ; => Coffee 1000, Coffee 1000")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "There's no indication that there is a difference between these two objects. If they weren't shown side-by-side, we wouldn't even know they were two different objects.")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "To add this information back into your custom pretty printers, you can use the"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "print-unreadable-object")
                                                                        "macro.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(defmethod print-object ((this beverage) stream)
  (print-unreadable-object (this stream :type t :identity t)
    (with-slots (name amount) this
      (format stream \"~a ~a\" name amount))))
(make-instance 'cold-beverage :name \"Coffee\" :amount 1000)
                                        ; => #<COLD-BEVERAGE Coffee 1000 {7008A403A3}>")))))
