                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(progn
 (eval-when (:compile-toplevel) (sb-c:%compiler-defun 'hello t nil nil))
 (sb-impl::%defun 'hello
                  (sb-int:named-lambda hello
                      (name)
                    (block hello (print name)))))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Because macros can expand into more macros, you may be able to expand more macros after the first expansion.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defun hello (names)
  (loop :for name :in names
        :do (format t \"Hello, ~a.~&\" name)))
;; expands into
(progn
 (eval-when (:compile-toplevel) (sb-c:%compiler-defun 'hello t nil nil))
 (sb-impl::%defun 'hello
                  (sb-int:named-lambda hello
                      (names)
                    (block hello
                      (loop :for name :in names
                            :do (format t \"Hello, ~a.~&\" name))))))
;; which further expands into... 
(progn
 (eval-when (:compile-toplevel) (sb-c:%compiler-defun 'hello t nil nil))
 (sb-impl::%defun 'hello
                  (sb-int:named-lambda hello
                      (names)
                    (block hello
                      (block nil
                        (let ((name nil)
                              (#:l548
                               (sb-kernel:the* (list :use-annotations t :source-form names) names)))
                          (declare (ignorable #:l548)
                                   (ignorable name))
                          (tagbody
                           sb-loop::next-loop
                            (when (endp #:l548) (go sb-loop::end-loop))
                            (sb-loop::loop-desetq name (car #:l548))
                            (sb-loop::loop-desetq #:l548 (cdr #:l548))
                            (format t \"Hello, ~a.~&\" name)
                            (go sb-loop::next-loop)
                           sb-loop::end-loop)))))))
;; and further...
(progn
 (eval-when (:compile-toplevel) (sb-c:%compiler-defun 'hello t nil nil))
 (sb-impl::%defun 'hello
                  (sb-int:named-lambda hello
                      (names)
                    (block hello
                      (block nil
                        (let ((name nil)
                              (#:l551
                               (sb-kernel:the* (list :use-annotations t :source-form names) names)))
                          (declare (ignorable #:l551)
                                   (ignorable name))
                          (tagbody
                           sb-loop::next-loop
                            (if (endp #:l551)
                                (go sb-loop::end-loop))
                            (setq name (car #:l551))
                            (setq #:l551 (cdr #:l551))
                            (format t \"Hello, ~a.~&\" name)
                            (go sb-loop::next-loop)
                           sb-loop::end-loop)))))))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "After calling"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "macroexpand-step")
                                                                      "the first time, you can expand one more step with"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "e")
                                                                      ".")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "You can undo one expansion at a time with"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "u")
                                                                      "or completely revert all expansions everywhere with"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "q")
                                                                      ".")))
                                                                (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                  (h2 :id "defining-macros" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                    "Defining Macros")
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "As you can see, macros significantly reduce the amount of visual noise in the code and make it easier to understand. But after looking at the code it expands into, you might wonder how the heck you even get started writing a macro at all?")
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "To begin defining a macro, first you need to do some wishful thinking.")
                                                                  (ul :class "org-ul"
                                                                    (li
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Write the desired call."))
                                                                    (li
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Write the desired expansion."))
                                                                    (li
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Construct macro parameter list from call.")))
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "For example, let's say you want to define a"
                                                                    (code
                                                                      "when-let")
                                                                    "macro that combines"
                                                                    (code
                                                                      "let")
                                                                    "and"
                                                                    (code
                                                                      "when")
                                                                    "into one form. First, you begin with the macro call you want to have:")
                                                                  (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                    (pre
                                                                      (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                        "(when-let (user (get-user id))
  (welcome-message user)
  (redirect-to-dashboard user))")))
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "Then, you write the code you want it to expand into:")
                                                                  (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                    (pre
                                                                      (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                        "(let ((user (get-user id)))
  (when user
    (welcome-message user)
    (redirect-to-dashboard user)))")))
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "Finally, you write the macro definition.")
                                                                  (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                    (pre
                                                                      (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                        "(defmacro when-let ((var expression) &body body)
  `(let ((,var ,expression))
     (when ,var
       ,@body)))")))
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "Before we go further, first you need to understand backquotes.")
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "backquotes" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Backquotes")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "In the previous code, you saw a backquote in the form"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "`(let ...)")
                                                                      ". Backquotes are like normal single-quotes--they are an abbreviation of"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "quote")
                                                                      ", which returns the literal representation of some code.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(quote (+ 2 2))
                                        ; => (+ 2 2)
'(+ 2 2)
                                        ; => (+ 2 2)
`(+ 2 2)
                                        ; => (+ 2 2)")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Notice that those symbols aren't interpreted. They and the list they are included in are returned as-is.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Backquotes have an important feature: you can tell the interpreter to actually evaluate some of parts of the code.")
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "comma-in-backquotes" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "Comma In Backquotes")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "To tell the interpreter to evaluate parts inside a backquoted form, type"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          ",")
                                                                        "before the part you want evaluated.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(let ((a 2)
      (b 3))
  `((+ ,a ,b) is ,(+ a b)))
                                        ; => ((+ 2 3) IS 5)")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "There are some rules you have to follow when using backquotes:")
                                                                      (ul :class "org-ul"
                                                                        (li
                                                                          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                            "A comma must follow a backquote."))
                                                                        (li
                                                                          (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                            "A comma can't follow another comma.")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "For example:")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(let ((a 2)
      (b 3))
  ;; Added commas    v  v
  `((+ ,a ,b) is ,(+ ,a ,b)))
;; Error:
;; Comma not inside a backquote.

;;   Stream: #<dynamic-extent STRING-INPUT-STREAM (unavailable) from \"(let ((a...\">
;;    [Condition of type SB-INT:SIMPLE-READER-ERROR]")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "If we add the commas to the second"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "a")
                                                                        "and"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "b")
                                                                        ", since the outer"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "(+ ...)")
                                                                        "form is already preceded with a comma, we get that error."))
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "comma-at-sign-in-backquotes" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "Comma At-Sign In Backquotes")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "In the"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "when-let")
                                                                        "macro, we also saw"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          ",@body")
                                                                        ". The"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          ",@")
                                                                        "\"splices\" the form into the backquoted code--removing the outermost parentheses.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(let ((a 5)
      (b '(1 2 3))
      (c 9))
  `(+ ,a ,@b ,c))
                                        ; => (+ 5 1 2 3 9)")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          ",@")
                                                                        "is commonly used with macros that take an arbitrary number of arguments and passing those arguments along to another form that also takes an arbitrary number of arguments. That's what the"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "body")
                                                                        "parameter for"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "when-let")
                                                                        "is.")))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "back-to-when-let" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Back to =when-let=")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Getting back to constructing a macro, after having the call and expansion prepared, you need to look at the parts that are common between them, and then make those parameters in the"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "defmacro")
                                                                      "lambda-list.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "For example, look at"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "user")
                                                                      ". It's in the expansion code three times:")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(let ((user ...))
 (... user
   (... user))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "and in the macro call twice:")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(when-let (user ...)
  (... user))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Which means a parameter in the"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "when-let")
                                                                      "definition needs to correspond to this variable.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defmacro when-let ((var ...)...)
  ...)")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "...and any instance of"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "var")
                                                                      "in the body of the macro definition needs to be preceded with a comma.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defmacro when-let ((var ...)...)
  `(let ((,var ...))
     (when ,var
       ...)))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "The same goes for"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "(get-user id)")
                                                                      ". It appears once in the expansion and once in the macro call.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(let ((... (get-user id)))
 (... ...
   (... ...)))

(when-let (... (get-user id))
  ...)")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "So it gets a spot in the parameter list of the macro:")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defmacro when-let ((... expression) ...)
  ...)")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "And where"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "expression")
                                                                      "appears in the macro body, it's preceded with a comma.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defmacro when-let ((... expression) ...)
  `(let ((... ,expression))
     ...))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "The calls to"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "(welcome-message user)")
                                                                      "and"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "(redirect-to-dashboard user)")
                                                                      "are actually in a space where we expect any arbitrary number of arbitrary forms. For that, we use a"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "&body")
                                                                      "parameter and splice it in with"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        ",@")
                                                                      ".")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defmacro when-let ((... ...) &body body)
  `(let ((... ...))
     (when ...
       ,@body)))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Altogether:")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defmacro when-let ((var expression) &body body)
  `(let ((,var ,expression))
     (when ,var
       ,@body)))"))))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "destructuring-arbitrary-list-structures-in-parameters" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Destructuring Arbitrary List Structures In Parameters")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "In the example of"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "when-let")
                                                                      ", we saw something strange in the lambda-list:")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          ";;                  v              v
(defmacro when-let ((var expression) &body body)
  ...)")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "What's going on there?")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Macros can take any list structure as a parameter and destructure them--binding parameters to elements within the list passed to the macro. To understand this characteristic of macro parameters, first we need to understand destructuring, represented best by"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "destructuring-bind")
                                                                      ".")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "destructuring-bind")
                                                                      "takes an arbitrary list structure and binds the elements of the list to local variables.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(let ((people '((\"Micah\" 40 (\"Lisp\" \"Hiking\" \"Photography\"))
                (\"Guy\" 71 (\"Engineering\" \"Frogs\" \"Education\"))
                (\"Joe\" 50 (\"Games\" \"Civilization\" \"Finding Good Women\")))))
  (dolist (person people)
    (destructuring-bind (name age (interest1 interest2 interest3)) person
      (print interest1))))
                                        ; \"Lisp\" 
                                        ; \"Engineering\" 
                                        ; \"Games\"  => NIL")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "The first argument to"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "destructuring-bind")
                                                                      "is a lambda-list of the variables to bind. The key is that it can bind any arbitrary element in any arbitrary list structure directly. All you need to do is mimic the structure of the list in the parameter list to"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "destructuring-bind")
                                                                      ".")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(let ((tree '(1 (2 (3 4) 5 ((6 ((7))))))))
  (destructuring-bind (a (b (c d) e ((f ((g)))))) tree
    (format t \"~a + ~a = ~a\" d f (+ d f))))
                                        ; 4 + 6 = 10 => NIL")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Macros can similarly destructure lists in their parameters list:")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defmacro add-elements ((a (b (c))))
  (+ a b c))

(add-elements (1 (2 (3))))
                                        ; => 6 (3 bits, #x6, #o6, #b110)")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "It's important to remember that we didn't call"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "(add-elements '(1 (2 (3)))")
                                                                      "or"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "(add-elements (list 1 (2 (3)))")
                                                                      ": those are both single elements. With a function, this would be an invalid call because the 3 (the innermost element) would be interpreted as a function-name, the Lisp evaluator would look for it, and not find it.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "However, macros have the previous macro expansion/compilation step, so the form"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "(1 (2 (3)))")
                                                                      "is valid: the macro would be expanded"
                                                                      (i
                                                                        "before")
                                                                      "the elements are evaluated.")))
                                                                (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                  (h2 :id "redefining-macros" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                    "Redefining Macros")
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "One thing to keep in mind with macros is that if you make a macro, use the macro to write some code and compile that code, if you redefine the macro, you also need to"
                                                                    (i
                                                                      "recompile the other code")
                                                                    ". Otherwise, that code is using the old macro expansion and not the new one."))
                                                                (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                  (h2 :id "determining-when-to-use-macros" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                    "Determining When To Use Macros")
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "As I said before, the general rule is to be conservative with your creation of macros. But there"
                                                                    (i
                                                                      "are")
                                                                    "times when you just gotta use the facilities that a macro provides.")
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "transformation" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Transformation")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Macros allow you to expand into different forms based on the arguments you send to it--"
                                                                      (i
                                                                        "before the arguments are evaluated")
                                                                      ". Consider the macro"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "setf")
                                                                      ".")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defvar *lang*)
(defstruct vehicle
  make
  model
  color)
(defclass person ()
  ((name :initarg :name :initform nil :accessor person-name)
   (age :initarg :age :initform nil :accessor person-age)))
(defparameter *cruiser* (make-vehicle :make \"Toyota\" :model \"Land Cruiser 70\" :color \"Beige\"))
(defparameter *micah* (make-instance 'person :name \"Micah\" :age 40))
(defparameter *list* '(1 2 3))

(setf *lang* \"Japanese\")
(setf (car *list*) 11)
(setf (vehicle-color *cruiser*) \"White\")
(setf (person-age *micah*) 25)")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "The calls to"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "setf")
                                                                      "expand to:")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(setq *lang* \"Japanese\")
(sb-kernel:%rplaca *list* 11)
(let* ((#:*cruiser*575 *cruiser*) (#:new574 \"White\"))
  (funcall #'(setf vehicle-color) #:new574 #:*cruiser*575))
(let* ((#:*micah*579 *micah*) (#:new578 25))
  (funcall #'(setf person-age) #:new578 #:*micah*579))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "The"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "setf")
                                                                      "macro looks at the arguments it receives and decides how to expand based on what it gets. If it sees"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "(car ...)")
                                                                      "then it uses"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "rplaca")
                                                                      ", if it sees another function like"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "(person-age ...)")
                                                                      "then it calls a generic function"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "setf")
                                                                      "with the"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "PERSON-AGE")
                                                                      "setter sent to it.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "It does this without evaluating the expressions passed to it--it only knows the literal representations of the forms. The code is the data it works with. If you need to transform code based on the shape of its inputs, you might need a macro."))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "binding" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Binding")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "As I said before, symbols aren't evaluated at expansion/compilation time, so if you want to bind symbols to values, macros are probably what you need. That's why"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "defun")
                                                                      ", etc. are macros."))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "conditional-evaluation" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Conditional Evaluation")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Because macros can transform code and control the evaluation of code, when you need to control the order of evaluation or whether a form gets evaluated at all, you might need a macro. That's why"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "if")
                                                                      ","
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "when")
                                                                      ","
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "unless")
                                                                      ", etc. conditional forms are macros."))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "wrapping-an-environment" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Wrapping An Environment")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "When you want to create a lexical environment like the"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "with-")
                                                                      "family of macros do, then you probably want a macro.")))
                                                                (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                  (h2 :id "determining-when-not-to-use-macros" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                    "Determining When Not To Use Macros")
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "There are certain situations under which you absolutely can't use macros. Macros can't be used as data, in the same way functions can.")
                                                                  (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                    (pre
                                                                      (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                        "(mapcar #'my-macro data) ; <- Error")))
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "Only functions can be passed to higher-order functions like"
                                                                    (code
                                                                      "mapcar")
                                                                    ","
                                                                    (code
                                                                      "reduce")
                                                                    ","
                                                                    (code
                                                                      "remove-if-not")
                                                                    ", etc.")
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "And of course, always keep in mind that if you are trying to develop a DSL, you might be overcomplicating things. If you want to collaborate with others, and you want to write DSLs, you better make them"
                                                                    (i
                                                                      "good")
                                                                    "."))
                                                                (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                  (h2 :id "variable-capture-hygiene" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                    "Variable Capture & Hygiene")
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "Macros can be tough to debug. That's partially because macros are generally harder to read because you have to keep the"
                                                                    (i
                                                                      "expansion")
                                                                    "code and"
                                                                    (i
                                                                      "expander")
                                                                    "code in your head at the same time.")
                                                                  (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                    "But macros are also more difficult to debug because they are subject to a unique class of bugs called variable capture. The subject of macro hygiene is primarily concerned with avoiding this class of bugs.")
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "examples-of-macros-vulnerable-to-variable-capture" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Examples Of Macros Vulnerable To Variable Capture")
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "free-variables-same-binding-context" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "Free Variables & Same Binding Context")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "The simplest example of a macro that's vulnerable to variable capture is a macro that returns a free variable.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(defmacro might-get-captured1 ()
  '(+ x 1))")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Why is this macro vulnerable? Because it doesn't return"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "'(+ x 1)")
                                                                        ". It"
                                                                        (i
                                                                          "expands into")
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "(+ x 1)")
                                                                        ", which is then evaluated at runtime.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(might-get-captured1) ; => Error: The variable X is unbound.
(let ((x 1))
  (might-get-captured1))
                                        ; => 2 (2 bits, #x2, #o2, #b10)")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Try expanding the code with"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "SPC m m")
                                                                        "("
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "macrostep-expand")
                                                                        ") to verify.")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Compare to a function:")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(defun cant-capture-me ()
  '(+ x 1))
(cant-capture-me)
                                        ; => (+ X 1)")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "So it's important to remember that quotes/backquotes in functions return literal representations, whereas macros use quotes/backquotes as templates for expanding into code-to-be-evaluated.")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "In addition to macros with free variables, macros that bind multiple variables within one"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "let")
                                                                        "are also vulnerable to capture. Consider the following macro:")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(defmacro might-get-captured2 (variable)
  `(let ((x 1)
         (,variable 0))
     (values x ,variable)))")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "If we call it like this:")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(let ((y 5))
  (might-get-captured2 y))")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "What do you expect the return values to be?")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(let ((y 5))
  (might-get-captured2 y))
                                        ; => 1, 0
;; Expanded
(let ((y 5))
  (let ((x 1) (y 0))
    (values x y)))")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Or what about this wombo combo:")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(let ((x 5))
  (might-get-captured2 x))")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "What is the return value? It's an error because"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "x")
                                                                        "occurs twice in the expanded"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "let")
                                                                        "form.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            ";; Expanded
(let ((x 5))
  (let ((x 1) (x 0))
    (values x x)))"))))
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "body-forms-containing-variables-in-macro" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "Body Forms Containing Variables In Macro")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "You don't know what symbols could be in a"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "&body")
                                                                        "parameter of a macro. A symbol used in the macro may get used in the"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "&body")
                                                                        "as well.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(defmacro might-get-captured3 (&body body)
  `(let ((x 5))
     (+ x ,@body)))")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Because the"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "body")
                                                                        "expands into an environment where"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "x")
                                                                        "is bound to the value 5, if the symbol"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "x")
                                                                        "appears in the"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "body")
                                                                        ", it will likely be overwritten in rebound by the macro's"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "leg")
                                                                        "context.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(let ((x 70)
      (y 50))
  (might-get-captured3
    (+ x y)))
                                        ; => 60 (6 bits, #x3C, #o74, #b111100)")))))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "avoiding-variable-capture" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Avoiding Variable Capture")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "These are general coding patterns that help you avoid variable capture.")
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "better-names-for-global-variables" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "Better Names For Global Variables")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Make sure you name global variables using the"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "*...*")
                                                                        "convention."))
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "assign-parameters-to-local-variables" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "Assign Parameters To Local Variables")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Instead of using parameters directly...")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            ";; Vulnerable
(defmacro comes-before-p (x y sequence)
  `(let ((sequence ,sequence))
     (< (position ,x sequence)
        (position ,y sequence))))

(comes-before-p 1 5 '(1 2 3 4 5))
 ; => T")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "...assign parameters to local variables before using them.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(defmacro comes-before-p (x y sequence)
  `(let ((sequence ,sequence)
         (xvar ,x)                         ; different variable names
         (yvar ,y))                        ; different variable names
     (< (position xvar sequence)
        (position yvar sequence))))"))))
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "define-macros-in-separate-packages" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "Define Macros In Separate Packages")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "To some extent, simply following the more modern One-Package-Per-File convention for factoring projects can also prevent some instances of variable capture. If you have"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "my-macro")
                                                                        "with symbol"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "x")
                                                                        "inside it, if someone uses"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "my-macro")
                                                                        "in their own package with an"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "x")
                                                                        "symbol, they will actually be two different symbols:"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "my-macro-package::x")
                                                                        "and"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "their-package::x")
                                                                        "."))
                                                                    (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                      (h4 :id "use-gensym" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                        "Use =gensym=")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Even if you give variables different names, and even if you give them names that others are unlikely to use, you have no guarantees that they will"
                                                                        (i
                                                                          "never")
                                                                        "be used by users of your macro.")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Instead, you can create"
                                                                        (i
                                                                          "anonymous symbols")
                                                                        "with"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "gensym")
                                                                        ".")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(gensym)
                                        ; => #:G586")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Every time you call"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "gensym")
                                                                        ", it will generate a symbol with a unique name.")
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Above, we expanded several different calls to"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "setf")
                                                                        "to show how it transforms based on the data it's passed. When we passed it"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "(vehicle-color *cruiser*)")
                                                                        ", it expanded into this:")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(let* ((#:*cruiser*575 *cruiser*) (#:new574 \"White\"))
  (funcall #'(setf vehicle-color) #:new574 #:*cruiser*575))")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "You can see the variables generated by"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "gensym")
                                                                        ":"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "#:*cruiser*575")
                                                                        "and"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "#:new574")
                                                                        ". By default, symbols generated with"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "gensym")
                                                                        "are prefixed with"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "G")
                                                                        ", but we can change that:")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(gensym \"*CRUISER*\")
                                        ; => #:*CRUISER*592")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "We can even change the suffix number (usually derived from"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "*gensym-counter*")
                                                                        ") if we pass an integer.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(gensym 500)
                                        ; => #:G500")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Importantly, these anonymous symbols aren't interned, so you can't even find them if you go searching.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(find-symbol \"*CRUISER*592\" )
                                        ; => NIL, NIL")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "And in fact, even if they appear to have the same name, two symbols generated with"
                                                                        (code
                                                                          "gensyms")
                                                                        "are still entirely different objects in memory.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(let ((a (gensym 100))
      (b (gensym 100)))
  (values a b))
                                        ; => #:G100, #:G100

(let ((a (gensym 100))
      (b (gensym 100)))
  (eq a b))
                                        ; => NIL")))
                                                                      (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                        "Once you find a variable that can possibly be captured, saving it to an anonymous symbol is a bulletproof way to avoid capture.")
                                                                      (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                        (pre
                                                                          (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                            "(defmacro comes-before-p (x y sequence)
  (let ((xvar (gensym))
        (yvar (gensym)))
    `(let ((sequence ,sequence)
           (,xvar ,x) 
           (,yvar ,y))
       (< (position ,xvar sequence)
          (position ,yvar sequence)))))")))))))
                                                              (article :class "almighty-chapter"
                                                                (h1 :id "organizing-code" :class "almighty-chapter-title"
                                                                  "ORGANIZING CODE")
                                                                (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                  (h2 :id "packages" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                    "Packages")
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "what-are-packages" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "What Are Packages?")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Packages are namespaces for symbols."))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "defining-packages" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Defining Packages")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Packages are defined with"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "defpackage")
                                                                      ".")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defpackage #:my-package
  (:use #:cl))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "my-package")
                                                                      "inherits or \"uses\" all of the external symbols of"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "cl")
                                                                      ", a nickname for the"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "common-lisp")
                                                                      "package, which contains all of the standard Common Lisp symbols.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(describe 'cl:defun)
                                        ; COMMON-LISP:DEFUN
                                        ;   [symbol]

                                        ; DEFUN names a macro:
                                        ;   Lambda-list: (NAME LAMBDA-LIST &BODY BODY)
                                        ;   Documentation:
                                        ;     Define a function at top level.
                                        ;   Source file: SYS:SRC;CODE;MACROS.LISP
                                        ;  => ; No value")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "If you don't include this line, you will need to add a package-qualifier to all of the symbols built into Common Lisp.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defpackage #:messy-package)
(in-package #:messy-package)

(defun hello-world ()
  (print \"Hello world\"))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "If you evaluate this code, you'll get a strange error:")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "The variable HELLO-WORLD is unbound.
   [Condition of type COMMON-LISP:UNBOUND-VARIABLE]")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Why? Because the"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "defun")
                                                                      "special operator is actually a"
                                                                      (i
                                                                        "macro")
                                                                      "whose first argument is a name for the function you are defining. Because it's a macro, the order of operations is to first"
                                                                      (i
                                                                        "expand")
                                                                      "the macro and then execute the code. During the macro expansion, the"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "hello-world")
                                                                      "symbol will be interned and its"
                                                                      (i
                                                                        "function name")
                                                                      "value will be bound to"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "hello-world")
                                                                      ".")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "However, because we didn't"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        ":use #:cl")
                                                                      ","
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "defun")
                                                                      "is interpreted as the name of a"
                                                                      (i
                                                                        "function")
                                                                      ", which requires first that all inner forms be evaluated and their values returned. And since"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "hello-world")
                                                                      "isn't bound to any value yet, we get the above error.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "All that is to say, unless you're a Lisp wizard concocting a sexp brew, you should be adding"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "(:use #:cl)")
                                                                      "to all of your package definitions."))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "using-importing-exporting" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Using, Importing & Exporting")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Let's expand the example:")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defpackage #:my-package
  (:use #:cl)
  (:export #:*global*))

(in-package #:my-package)

(defparameter *global* \"This is a global variable.\")

(defpackage #:your-package
  (:use #:cl)
  (:import-from #:my-package))
(in-package #:your-package)

(print my-package:*global*)
                                        ; \"This is a global variable.\"  => \"This is a global variable.\"
(symbol-package 'my-package:*global*)
                                        ; => #<PACKAGE \"MY-PACKAGE\">

(let ((my-package:*global* \"Symbol from MY-PACKAGE lexically rebound in YOUR-PACKAGE\"))
  my-package:*global*)
                                        ; => \"Symbol from MY-PACKAGE lexically rebound in YOUR-PACKAGE\"

(defparameter *global* \"Global variable interned in YOUR-PACKAGE.\")

(symbol-package '*global*)
                                        ; => #<PACKAGE \"YOUR-PACKAGE\">")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "By importing packages, you can reuse symbol names without naming conflicts.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "You may also want to import the symbol, allowing you to use it without a package-name qualifier.")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defpackage #:your-package
  (:use #:cl)
  (:import-from #:my-package
                #:*global*))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "If you start this way, then you won't need a package name qualifier when you use it."))
                                                                  (article :class "almighty-section"
                                                                    (h3 :id "shadowing-and-conflicts" :class "almighty-section-title"
                                                                      "Shadowing And Conflicts")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "This is not the case if you"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "use")
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "my-package")
                                                                      ". Change the definition of"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "your-package")
                                                                      ":")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defpackage #:your-package
  (:use #:cl #:my-package))")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "If you compile that form you will get this error:")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-text"
                                                                          "USE-PACKAGE (MY-PACKAGE:*GLOBAL*) causes name-conflicts in
#<PACKAGE \"YOUR-PACKAGE\"> between the following symbols:
  YOUR-PACKAGE::*GLOBAL*, MY-PACKAGE:*GLOBAL*
   [Condition of type SB-EXT:NAME-CONFLICT]

Restarts:
 0: [KEEP-OLD] Keep YOUR-PACKAGE::*GLOBAL* accessible in YOUR-PACKAGE (shadowing MY-PACKAGE:*GLOBAL*).
 1: [TAKE-NEW] Make MY-PACKAGE:*GLOBAL* accessible in YOUR-PACKAGE (uninterning YOUR-PACKAGE::*GLOBAL*).
 2: [RESOLVE-CONFLICT] Resolve conflict.
 3: [ABORT] Abort compilation.
 4: [*ABORT] Return to SLY's top level.
 5: [ABORT] abort thread (#<THREAD tid=20391 \"slynk-worker\" RUNNING {7005097833}>)")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Now you'll have several different"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "restarts")
                                                                      "to choose from, including"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "TAKE-NEW")
                                                                      ","
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "KEEP-OLD")
                                                                      ", etc. and a bit of a mess to clean up. My recommendation is to only use"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        ":use")
                                                                      "sparingly in situations you know you aren't going to have conflicts later (like in your testing packages).")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "If you choose"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "KEEP-OLD")
                                                                      ", you will"
                                                                      (i
                                                                        "shadow")
                                                                      "the"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "my-package:*global*")
                                                                      "with"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "your-package:*global*")
                                                                      ". Shadowing means that the imported symbol is hidden, allowing the same symbol in the current package.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "My experience has been that doing anything short of aborting,"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "unintern")
                                                                      "ing the symbol or"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "unuse-package")
                                                                      "ing the package I'm using leads to frustration. You're better off not using"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        ":use")
                                                                      "in the first place.")
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Even if you do as I recommend you might still have this name conflict problem. Consider this situation:")
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defpackage #:my-package
  (:use #:cl)
  (:export #:my-function))
(in-package #:my-package)

(defun my-function () (print \"my-function\"))

(defpackage #:my-other-package
  (:use #:cl)
  (:import-from #:my-package))

(in-package #:my-other-package)

(defun my-other-function ()
  (my-package:my-function))
(my-other-function)")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "Right now, we have a couple of problems.")
                                                                    (ol :class "org-ol"
                                                                      (li
                                                                        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                          "I forgot to"
                                                                          (b
                                                                            "export the symbol from my-package")
                                                                          "."))
                                                                      (li
                                                                        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                          "I don't have a package-qualifier attached to"
                                                                          (code
                                                                            "my-function")
                                                                          "when I try to use it.")))
                                                                    (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                      "When I try to compile"
                                                                      (code
                                                                        "my-other-function")
                                                                      ", I'll get a style-warning about an undefined function. At this point, there are two options:")
                                                                    (ol :class "org-ol"
                                                                      (li
                                                                        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                          "Add a package name qualifier, as in"
                                                                          (code
                                                                            "(my-package:my-function)")
                                                                          "; or"))
                                                                      (li
                                                                        (p :class "almighty-book-paragraph"
                                                                          "Add the function symbol in the imports as below")))
                                                                    (figure :class "almighty-code-block"
                                                                      (pre
                                                                        (code :class "almighty-src almighty-src-lisp"
                                                                          "(defpackage #:my-other-package
  (:use #:cl)
  (:import-from #:my-package
                #:my-function))
(in-package #:my-other-package)")))
